opens with an introduction presenting basic theoretical frameworks, followed by three application sections dealing with clinical practice, research and theory, and public policy. In each, the discussion takes the form of a conversation, as the authors first consider essentialist and constructionist approaches to the topic at hand. These thoughts, in turn, are followed by responses from distinguished scholars chosen for their expertise in a particular area. By providing an array of comments and thoughtful responses to topics surrounding psychology's approaches to sexual orientation, this valuable study sheds new light on the contrasting views held in the field and the ways in which essentialist and constructionist understandings may be applied to specific practices and policies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBisexualityxPsychological aspects. 0aBisexualsxMental health services. 0aGaysxMental health services. 0aHomosexualityxPsychological aspects. 0aPsychotherapy. 0aSexual orientationxPsychological aspects. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Human Sexuality (see also SOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Sexuality).2bisacsh1 aBohan, Janis S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCass, Vivienne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaldeman, Douglas C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIasenza, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Fritz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOmoto, Allen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRussell, Glenda M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRussell, Glenda M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTiefer, Leonore, econtributor.4ctb4ht